## The five reusable building blocks

Most wishlist items reduce to a handful of shared pieces. Build these once; reuse
everywhere.

::: fields
E1 — npm publish: `@chromamark/renderer` public on npm. Unblocks CDN, CLI, playground, editors.
E2 — CLI / static compiler: `.cm` → one self-contained HTML file (theme inlined, no CDN).
E3 — GFM transpiler: `.cm` → GitHub-flavored Markdown (Alerts + badge images + `<details>`). The key to every sanitized GitHub surface.
E4 — Python port: re-implement the plugin on `markdown-it-py` (same API). Unblocks Python SDK + Jupyter.
E5 — LLM quick reference: a compact prompt-ready cheat sheet.
:::

::: tip Why E3 matters most
GitHub strips CSS on its "prose" surfaces, so our real theme can't render there.
But `.cm` maps cleanly onto things GitHub _does_ support natively — that's what
makes items 1, 9, and 11 possible at all.
:::

---

## 1 · GitHub integration

The single most important finding: **GitHub has two rendering tiers**, and they
demand different strategies.

### Tier A — GitHub Pages (full fidelity)

::: fields
Verdict: [!success Feasible]
Fidelity: [!success Full CSS/JS]
Effort: [!warning Medium]
Needs: E1 (CDN) or E2 (prerender)
:::

Pages is a plain static host — all HTML/CSS/JS allowed. Our browser bundle already
works here (`<script data-chromamark-auto>` + `.chromamark` blocks), or precompile
with the CLI. This is the best GitHub surface for ChromaMark and needs nothing new
beyond publishing.

### Tier B — README, PR comments, issues, Actions job summaries (sanitized)

::: fields
Verdict: [!warning Partial — via transpile]
Fidelity: [!warning Degraded but styled]
Effort: [!warning Medium]
Needs: E3
:::

These surfaces run GitHub's Markdown sanitizer: **no `<style>`, no `class`/`id`,
no `<script>`, inline `<svg>` stripped.** Our exact theme cannot render. But a
transpiler (E3) maps ChromaMark onto GitHub-native equivalents:

| ChromaMark | GitHub-flavored Markdown target |
| ---------- | ------------------------------- |
| `::: warning` / `info` / `tip` / `danger` blocks | **GitHub Alerts** `> [!WARNING]` / `[!NOTE]` / `[!TIP]` / `[!CAUTION]` (GA; render on README/issues/PRs/comments) |
| `[!pass]` / `[!fail]` pills | **badge images** (shields.io or self-hosted SVG) — `<img>` is allowed on every surface |
| `::: details` | native `<details><summary>` (allowed) |
| `::: fields` | a two-column table |
| `[.tint]` colored text | bold + an emoji marker (no color) |
| `[=87%]` meter | a progress badge image or a unicode bar |

::: details danger Hard limits — what is NOT possible on Tier B
- Our CSS-based colors/pills cannot render; the closest is Alerts (5 fixed colors) + badge images.
- Only the six semantic tones map to Alerts; custom `color=#hex` has no equivalent.
- Inline `<svg>`, `<script>`, `<style>`, `class`, and `id` are all stripped.
- Badge images add network round-trips (camo-proxied) — fine for a report, not for hundreds of inline pills.
- "Colorized tags" become monochrome-ish shields; acceptable, not pixel-perfect.
:::

::: details info The four GitHub "pieces" you asked about
- **Actions rendering** — two modes: (a) an Action runs the CLI to build Pages/artifacts (full fidelity); (b) write transpiled GFM to `$GITHUB_STEP_SUMMARY` (Alerts + badges) for per-run reports.
- **README rendering** — commit a transpiled `README.md` (Alerts + badges + `<details>`) generated by the CLI in CI; keep the `.cm` source alongside.
- **Pages rendering** — Tier A, full fidelity (above).
- **PR comment rendering** — a GitHub Action/App posts a transpiled-GFM comment on each PR. No custom CSS, but Alerts + status badges read well.
:::

## 2 · npm package

::: fields
Verdict: [!success Feasible — do first]
Effort: [!success Low]
Impact: [!success High]
Needs: nothing (already structured for it)
:::

Publish `@chromamark/renderer` (public scoped) — the package already has `exports`,
`files`, a `prepublishOnly` build, and the browser bundle. Add npm provenance and
an `@chromamark` org. A thin `chromamark` CLI package (item 3) can ship beside it.

## 3 · CLI tooling

::: fields
Verdict: [!success Feasible — high leverage]
Effort: [!warning Medium]
Impact: [!success High]
Needs: E1
:::

Exactly your instinct: **precompile to static HTML, no CDN required.**

```
chromamark build report.cm -o report.html   # self-contained, theme inlined
chromamark build docs/ -o out/               # whole directory
cat report.cm | chromamark - --format html   # stdin → stdout
chromamark build report.cm --format md       # → GitHub-flavored Markdown (E3)
chromamark watch report.cm -o report.html    # live rebuild
```

One binary delivers static output **and** the GFM transpile — so it also powers
items 1 (README/PR/Actions) and 11 (Jekyll prerender).

## 4 · Python builder / output SDK

::: fields
Verdict: [!success Feasible — strong fit for the mission]
Effort: [!warning Medium]
Impact: [!success High]
Needs: E4 (for rendering only)
:::

Agents reach for Python to assemble reports, so a Python surface is well-aligned.
Two layers:

::: details open success 4a · Builder / emitter (pure Python, ship first)
A fluent API that emits `.cm` text — no renderer needed:

```python
doc = ChromaDoc()
doc.success("Deploy succeeded", body="3/3 replicas healthy")
doc.fields(region="eastus", coverage=doc.meter("info", "87%"))
doc.table(["Stage","Result"], [["unit", doc.pill("pass","247")]])
print(doc.render())   # -> ChromaMark string
```
Low effort, immediately useful for agent-generated reports.
:::

::: details info 4b · Full renderer via markdown-it-py (later)
`markdown-it-py` exposes the **same** `md.block.ruler.before(...)` /
`md.inline.ruler.before(...)` / token / render-rule API as our JS plugin, so the
containers/inline/critic rules port almost 1:1. Gives Python-native `.cm → HTML`
and unblocks Jupyter (item 10) with no Node dependency. Medium effort.
:::

## 5 · MCP angle

::: fields
Verdict: [!info Niche — small, optional]
Effort: [!success Low]
Impact: [!muted Low]
:::

Honest take: agents **emit ChromaMark as plain text**, so they don't need a tool to
_write_ it. The only worthwhile MCP surfaces:

- Expose the **quick reference + spec as an MCP resource/prompt**, so any MCP client can self-teach the format. [!info Mild value]
- A `render_chromamark` **tool** (cm → HTML) so an agent can preview/validate its own output. [!muted Marginal]

Recommendation: fold the quick-ref into an MCP resource _if_ we build a server for
another reason; don't build one just for this.

## 6 · LLM quick reference

::: fields
Verdict: [!success Do this now — best ROI]
Effort: [!success Low]
Impact: [!success High]
:::

A compact, example-first cheat sheet (a few hundred tokens) to drop into a system
prompt so any model emits valid ChromaMark. This is the most direct investment in
the "agents → humans" mission and costs almost nothing.

::: details tip Sketch of the reference
Ship as `docs/llms.txt` + a README section:
```
ChromaMark = Markdown + these:
  ::: success|info|tip|warning|danger|muted  Title … :::   (colored block)
  [!success PASS] [!fail 3] [!warn 12]                     (pill/badge)
  ::: details open  Summary … :::                          (collapsible)
  ::: fields \n Key: Value \n :::                          (key/value)
  [.danger text]   [=info 87%]   {++add++}{--del--}        (tint, meter, diff)
```
:::

## 7 · Other editor plugins (JetBrains / Sublime / Zed)

::: fields
Verdict: [!warning Mixed — highlighting cheap, previews expensive]
Effort: [!danger High for full plugins]
Impact: [!info Medium]
:::

Syntax highlighting is portable; live preview is the costly part per editor.

::: details warning Per-editor breakdown
- **Sublime Text** — reuse our TextMate grammar as a `.sublime-syntax`/`tmLanguage`. Highlighting only. [!success Low]
- **Zed** — needs a tree-sitter grammar + a small Rust/WASM extension; can inject into Markdown. [!warning Medium]
- **JetBrains** — a full IntelliJ-platform plugin (Kotlin) for file type + highlighting + a JCEF webview preview running our JS bundle. [!danger High]
- Recommendation: ship the Sublime grammar cheaply; defer Zed/JetBrains until there's demand.
:::

## 8 · Playground / demo site

::: fields
Verdict: [!success Feasible — great for adoption]
Effort: [!warning Medium]
Impact: [!success High]
Needs: E1
:::

Split-pane live editor → preview using the browser bundle, with a theme toggle,
an examples menu, and shareable URLs (source encoded in the `#hash`). Hosts on
GitHub Pages for free and doubles as marketing + the reference renderer.

## 9 · Syntax highlighting

::: fields
Verdict: [!success Feasible]
Effort: [!success Low–Medium]
Impact: [!info Medium]
:::

Two distinct things, both worth doing:

- **Editor highlighting** of ChromaMark syntax — we already have a VS Code injection grammar; generalize it (ties to item 7).
- **Code-fence highlighting inside rendered output** — wire markdown-it's `highlight` option to highlight.js/Prism so ` ```lang ` blocks inside `.cm` are colorized. Small optional add to the renderer.

## 10 · Jupyter / notebook integration

::: fields
Verdict: [!success Feasible]
Effort: [!warning Medium]
Impact: [!info Medium]
Needs: E4 (cleanest) or Node bridge
:::

Notebooks render HTML/CSS fully, so fidelity is excellent. Provide
`display_chromamark(src)` → `IPython.display.HTML(rendered + theme)`. The only
requirement is a renderer callable from Python — best via the markdown-it-py port
(4b); an interim version can shell out to the Node CLI.

## 11 · Jekyll integration

::: fields
Verdict: [!warning Partial — caveat on GitHub Pages]
Effort: [!warning Medium]
Impact: [!info Medium]
:::

::: details danger The GitHub Pages catch
GitHub Pages builds Jekyll in **safe mode**, which **disallows custom plugins**.
So a native Ruby `{% chromamark %}` tag only works if you build the site yourself
(e.g., in **GitHub Actions**) and deploy the output.
:::

Two paths that _do_ work on default Pages:
- **Client-side include** — drop our JS bundle into the theme; `.chromamark` blocks render in the browser. Zero build, works on stock Pages. [!success Recommended]
- **CI prerender** — run the CLI (E2) in Actions to emit static HTML, deploy that. Full fidelity, any plugin allowed. [!success Recommended]

A native Ruby plugin is extra work for little gain over these two.

